abstract: A company memo said they had been dismissed “for clear and repeated violations of our data security policies.”
snippet: A company memo said they had been dismissed “for clear and repeated violations of our data security policies.”
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Google on Monday fired four employees who had been active in labor organizing at the company, according to a memo that was seen by The New York Times.

abstract: Bryant Robert Mitchell said he was illegally searched during a traffic stop. The Utah Court of Appeals said the search was lawful because he was acting belligerently and was a known gang member.
snippet: Bryant Robert Mitchell said he was illegally searched during a traffic stop. The Utah Court of Appeals said the search was lawful because he was acting belligerently and was a known gang member.
lead_paragraph: A neo-Nazi gang member in Utah has lost his legal challenge to the practice of stop-and-frisk in the state, after an appeals court ruled that police officers had justifiable cause to search him after he behaved belligerently during a traffic stop in 2017.

abstract: The president presented the dog that took part in a raid that killed the Islamic State’s leader even as he is embroiled in a dispute over a war crimes case.
snippet: The president presented the dog that took part in a raid that killed the Islamic State’s leader even as he is embroiled in a dispute over a war crimes case.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The military dog who chased a terrorist to his death in October has recovered from his wounds and has since gone on “very important raids,” President Trump said on Monday as he stood near the dog during a last-minute appearance in the Rose Garden.

abstract: New Hampshire is as close to a must-win state as Mr. Sanders has, and, despite his overwhelming victory against Hillary Clinton in 2016, winning is far from a sure thing right now.

lead_paragraph: FRANKLIN, N.H. — Bernie Sanders is more than happy to remind New Hampshire about his big win in the state’s Democratic presidential primary almost four years ago.

abstract: Prolific, erudite and caustic in his wit, he surveyed the entire cultural landscape — films, plays, books, art — and saw little that he liked.
snippet: Prolific, erudite and caustic in his wit, he surveyed the entire cultural landscape — films, plays, books, art — and saw little that he liked.
lead_paragraph: John Simon, one of the nation’s most erudite, vitriolic and vilified culture critics, who illuminated and savaged a remarkable range of plays, films, literature and art works and their creators for more than a half-century, died on Sunday in Valhalla, N.Y. He was 94.

headline_print_headline: John Simon, Cultural Critic Who Penned Unsparing Reviews, Dies at 94

abstract: The most consistent theme of the day from Michael Bloomberg’s first in-person appearance as a presidential candidate was not the size of the crowd but the size of how much he’s spent on building political good will.
snippet: The most consistent theme of the day from Michael Bloomberg’s first in-person appearance as a presidential candidate was not the size of the crowd but the size of how much he’s spent on building political good will.
lead_paragraph: NORFOLK, VA. — Senator Kamala Harris declared her presidential candidacy on Martin Luther King’s Birthday and held her first rally before a crowd of 20,000 in Oakland, Calif., while her colleague Senator Elizabeth Warren addressed thousands on a bitter winter day in Lawrence, Mass., the site of a historic textile workers’ strike. Joseph R. Biden Jr., the former vice president, began his run for president before a crowd of union members in Pittsburgh before launching into a campaign swing that culminated with a rally in downtown Philadelphia.

headline_main: At First 2020 Campaign Stop, Bloomberg Boasts What His Money Can Do
headline_print_headline: In Muted Campaign Kickoff, Bloomberg Shows How Money Talks

abstract: Michael Bloomberg announced yesterday that he would run for the 2020 Democratic presidential nomination, but people are already arguing against one billionaire taking over office from another.
snippet: Michael Bloomberg announced yesterday that he would run for the 2020 Democratic presidential nomination, but people are already arguing against one billionaire taking over office from another.
lead_paragraph: Good morning. Charles Schwab said it would acquire TD Ameritrade for $26 billion — a deal that brings together two of the largest online brokerage firms totaling roughly $5 trillion in assets. (Was this email forwarded to you? Sign up here.)

headline_main: Michael Bloomberg, Hong Kong, Tiffany: Your Monday Briefing

abstract: The Democratic presidential candidates don’t want to simply defend abortion rights. They want to go on offense.
snippet: The Democratic presidential candidates don’t want to simply defend abortion rights. They want to go on offense.
lead_paragraph: The Democratic presidential field has coalesced around an abortion rights agenda more far-reaching than anything past nominees have proposed, according to a New York Times survey of the campaigns. The positions reflect a hugely consequential shift on one of the country’s most politically divisive issues.

abstract: Joe Biden leads with black voters, and Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders are making better inroads with younger ones than Kamala Harris and Cory Booker. In interviews, voters rejected the idea that racial representation equated to change.
